00:11:30.490 --> 00:11:33.180
So pretty easy to do.

00:11:33.180 --> 00:11:36.090
And I want to take a little
side track because

00:11:36.090 --> 00:11:37.890
I had to fake this.

00:11:37.890 --> 00:11:41.510
And I planned on actually having
this be a live demo.

00:11:41.510 --> 00:11:45.490
And it turns out there's some
interesting issues with

00:11:45.490 --> 00:11:49.580
capturing images of CSS 3D
transforms that make it

00:11:49.580 --> 00:11:50.110
impossible.

00:11:50.110 --> 00:11:52.930
So things like PhantomJS, which
a lot of people use for

00:11:52.930 --> 00:11:56.540
screenshots, don't actually
support those transforms.

00:11:56.540 --> 00:11:59.820
So I had to fake it here.

00:11:59.820 --> 00:12:03.160
But there's a couple issues
with this that I think are

00:12:03.160 --> 00:12:06.640
worth talking about with
relation to certain apps.

00:12:06.640 --> 00:12:07.890
So the Realtime API.

00:12:11.180 --> 00:12:13.540
When you have an app that uses
it, you don't have an explicit

00:12:13.540 --> 00:12:14.470
save point.

00:12:14.470 --> 00:12:18.130
So it's not always clear what
you should actually be

00:12:18.130 --> 00:12:20.070
snapshotting in terms
of the image.

00:12:20.070 --> 00:12:23.080
In this case, I did
this manually.

00:12:23.080 --> 00:12:25.690
I said, this is the point
that I want to save it.

00:12:25.690 --> 00:12:28.820
But if I have a user who's
making a serious move and

00:12:28.820 --> 00:12:32.870
they're playing for 5 or 10
minutes, do you wait for them

00:12:32.870 --> 00:12:34.960
to close their browser?

00:12:34.960 --> 00:12:36.810
What happens if you have
multiple people in there if

00:12:36.810 --> 00:12:39.540
one person closes and the
other person continues?

00:12:39.540 --> 00:12:41.650
So the idea is you don't want
to necessarily update the

00:12:41.650 --> 00:12:43.860
image too often.

00:12:43.860 --> 00:12:46.140
Basically you're just burning
through a quota.

00:12:46.140 --> 00:12:47.770
It's wasteful.

00:12:47.770 --> 00:12:50.410
And given that these are really
just snapshots at a

00:12:50.410 --> 00:12:52.710
point in time to help users
recognize it, you don't

00:12:52.710 --> 00:12:57.110
necessarily need to be super
accurate in terms of making

00:12:57.110 --> 00:13:02.180
sure that that preview is a
perfect representation of what

00:13:02.180 --> 00:13:05.100
the content of the file is
at any point in time.

00:13:05.100 --> 00:13:09.070
So you can do things a
little bit lazily.

00:13:09.070 --> 00:13:10.370
Defer things.

00:13:10.370 --> 00:13:12.930
And for something like the
Realtime API, a simple trick

00:13:12.930 --> 00:13:15.550
you can do, assuming that we
had a way to render this on

00:13:15.550 --> 00:13:18.970
the server, would be any time
that the file is changed,

00:13:18.970 --> 00:13:21.500
queue up some sort of event.

00:13:21.500 --> 00:13:23.640
Send this in the server,
send a time stamp.

00:13:23.640 --> 00:13:27.140
And then after some period of
time, 5, 10, 15 minutes later,

00:13:27.140 --> 00:13:30.030
then you can just snapshot
that file.

00:13:30.030 --> 00:13:33.770
And then if more collaborators
come along, you may want to

00:13:33.770 --> 00:13:37.450
coalesce all those different
modifications into one event.

00:13:37.450 --> 00:13:39.620
That way you're not burning
through your quota too quickly

00:13:39.620 --> 00:13:40.900
in order to keep this
stuff up to date.

00:13:40.900 --> 00:13:44.310
Really it's important, but you
don't want to necessarily kill

00:13:44.310 --> 00:13:46.830
yourself or burn through quota
too quickly in order to keep

00:13:46.830 --> 00:13:48.710
this information up to date.

00:13:48.710 --> 00:13:50.320
Same thing for indexable text.

00:13:50.320 --> 00:13:53.130
You can do the same thing
where you don't want to

00:13:53.130 --> 00:13:55.620
reindex on every word that
somebody's typing.

00:13:55.620 --> 00:13:59.260
Just do it at some reasonable
interval after there's a

00:13:59.260 --> 00:14:01.070
little bit of idleness.

00:14:01.070 --> 00:14:02.810
You know, because honestly,
people aren't going to go back

00:14:02.810 --> 00:14:04.800
and look for that file
immediately as soon as they're

00:14:04.800 --> 00:14:05.490
done editing.

00:14:05.490 --> 00:14:07.550
They're probably going to come
back the next day, the next

00:14:07.550 --> 00:14:09.450
week, or so on.

00:14:09.450 --> 00:14:13.690
So just put in a little delay
and you really should be fine.

00:14:13.690 --> 00:14:16.490
But anyway, I had planned on
making this all really nice

00:14:16.490 --> 00:14:20.960
and interactive until I ran into
issues with capturing the

00:14:20.960 --> 00:14:21.940
